msContents.summary: Guðmundar saga biskups. The saga of this manuscript (the so-called oldest saga) is a compilation of 'Prestssaga', 'Hrafns saga', 'Íslendinga saga', 'Arons saga' and annals. AM 399 4to was one of the manuscripts Peder Resen presented to the University Library in Copenhagen. This manuscript is one of the few to have survived from this library, which was consumed in the flames of the Great Fire of Copenhagen in 1728 as Árni Magnússon had borrowed it.

supportDesc.condition: A total of 12 leaves are missing at different places in between the surviving leaves. The lower part of fol 14 is torn out. Here and there smaller damages, tears etc. occur

layoutDesc.layout: Written in one line with 24 lines per page.

handDesc.handNote: The manuscript is beautifully written in a large, clear and distinct hand. Stefan Karlsson finds that this hand is identical with the one who, among other manuscripts, wrote the AM 122 a fol.

physDesc.additions: The originally blank fol. 1r contain one to six marginalia concerning the content. These are written in the seventeenth century by an untrained hand. Among younger additions to the manucript is the name Ásmundur Klemensson, and a man with this unusual name appears in various sources from the years 1497-1530.
physDesc.accMat: On an AM-slip Árni Magnússon wrote: Denne bog haver universitas Hafniensis laant mig ex Bibliothecâ Resenianâ 1706. og bör den af mig uskaddet at restitueres. A Magnussen. Another slip, written by Peder Resen is attached: Codex islandicus mss. in pergamento: agit de aliis atqve aliis Islandiæ Episcopis præsertim de Gudmundo Eposcopo Ariæ filio. Petri Resenii 1685 . The slip was possibly a former fly-leaf

history.origin: The manuscript was written in Iceland in the period 1330-1350 ( Stefán Karlsson 1983 xli ). Kålund's dating: ca. 1300 ( Katalog I 604 ).
history.provenance: The manuscript has belonged to Peder Resen, from whom it got its nickname. Nothing is known of the earlier history of the manuscript.
history.acquisition: AM 399 4to was one of the manuscripts Peder Resen presented to the University Library in Copenhagen but it was on loan to Árni Magnússon when the library burned down.
